WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Updates on Spark, MLflow, and the broader ML ecosystem

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
If you've never heard about Spark, this is what you need to know.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Mostly, there's a lot of data in this world.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
The World Bank reports that actually data is growing exponentially.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Basically, around every two years, you can expect that we have twice as much data.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And, you know, what do you do when you have a lot of data?

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Well, you can try a lot of things like, first of all, sampling your datasets,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
using tools like Arrow, getting a bigger machine, lots of different things.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
But when all fails, what you can do is split your data into multiple machines.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
And you can do that with something called Hadoop,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
which was a very popular tool for many years.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
But if you want to even kind of like provide better performance

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:15.000
and much more functionality, a better replacement for Hadoop, the runtime, is Apache Spark.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
So that's kind of like the intro.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
If you want to use Spark on R, like what do you do?

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Well, you use the sparklyr package.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And the great thing about the sparklyr package is that,

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.000
if you're already familiar with Deplier, you can basically reuse all your Deplier code

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
and then add a couple lines on top of it and read the data in a distributed fashion

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.000
and still use Deplier to scale your datasets.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
So that's pretty great.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.000
And it also works in a similar way with packages like Broom, Rlang expressions, and DBI.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
So how exactly do you use sparklyr?

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Well, first of all, if you don't have a cluster with a bunch of machines and a bunch of budget,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
don't worry, all you need to do is run spark install,

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:03.000
and that's basically going to install a local version of Spark in your local machine.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And then you use spark connect to connect to the cluster either locally

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
or if you happen to have like Yarn, Mesos, Kubernetes, or whatever,

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
you change the master parameter to the location of your cluster.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Then you can read and write data on CSV file formats,

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Parquet from Arrow is a great way of interoperating,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Avro, JSON, and a bunch of others like databases.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
You can also do data analysis with tools that you already know and love,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
like SQL using the DBI package or Deplier.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And you can run over 50 machine learning algorithms and feature transformers

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000
using the MLE library, which is provided by default on Spark.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
You can also grab those models and extract them out in a pipeline,

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:50.000
and then you can use those pipelines in production

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
or push them to Python or Java-enabled devices.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And you can also build extensions.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
We can't obviously provide support for all the functionality that you might want.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
So you can write extensions for Spark and R in Scala,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
or you can also use R extensions using Spark Apply.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And last but not least, one of the latest features added to Spark

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
was Spark Structured Streaming, which basically allows you to process

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
real-time datasets in Spark with the same set of functions

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
and also using things like Deplier.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
All right, so what have we been up to?

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Well, we started the SparklyR project back in 2016,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.000
and since then we've obviously added a bunch of features,

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:37.000
but I think it's more interesting to highlight that there's a bunch of

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
products and cloud services that have embraced SparklyR

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:42.000
to a different degree.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Some of them have provided blog posts and documentation on how to use it.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Some other cloud providers like Databricks and Qubole

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
have actually added first-class support in SparklyR for their clusters,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
which is pretty great.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.000
The last release of Spark was Spark 1.0,

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.000
where we added support for Apache Arrow,

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
and yes, we did get 40 times performance improvements,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
as Neil was mentioning.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:07.000
So that's pretty great.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.000
It's still optional, so you don't get Arrow by default.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
You need to install the Arrow package and then use it.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:17.000
And SparklyR 1.0 also added support for XGBoost, Broom, and TF Records.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
The talk today is more about SparklyR 1.0.1,

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
which we just released to CRAN,

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
and one of the new features that SparklyR 1.0.1 adds

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
is support for Delta Lake.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So what is Delta Lake?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Delta Lake is a new open-source project

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
which happens to be hosted with the Linux Foundation,

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
and what it adds, it gives Spark the ability to have ACID transactions,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:43.000
which is basically database-like properties

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
to use on top of your data lake.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Now, this doesn't mean that you should use...

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
This doesn't mean that you should replace your databases with Spark.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
That's not at all the goal of this project.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
But what it really allows you to do is to mix real-time data

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
with batch processing data on the same table.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:01.000
So in the past RStudio conference,

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
I had to do this demo where we used different types of functions,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.000
and to load streaming data against batch data.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And basically, you can replace all that with Delta Lake

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
because you don't need to worry about where the data is coming from.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.000
It just goes to the same source.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
And it also enables a few nice features,

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
like being able to find and use previous versions of your datasets,

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
which we'll see in a second.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:26.000
So how do you use Delta Lake from R?

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
You need to load the SparklyR package,

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
and then you connect as usual.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
But there's a new parameter called packages,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
so you want to specify packages equals Delta.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And then you basically use the functions to read and write data.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
You say, Spark write Delta, and you write a data frame.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
Here we have huge data frames with three rows,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.000
and we're replacing that huge data frame with another data frame with one row.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And basically, then if you ask Delta Lake for that particular dataset,

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
you just say, Spark read Delta,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
and you get that dataset right with one row.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
But what is interesting is you can also tell Delta,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
hey, give me the previous version that I just overwrote.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
And what that would give you back is the tree records that were initially there.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
All right, so more new features in SparklyR 101.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
Well, first of all, these are community extensions.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
So super exciting to see the community growing

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
and building extensions on top of SparklyR.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
There is two extensions on the genomics space.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
So if you're into genomics, there is one called VariantSpark

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.000
for doing genome-wide association studies.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
And one initial extension for using HAIL from Spark,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
which is currently in CRAN,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:39.000
but still probably still needs a few more releases to be fully usable.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
And there's another extension called Spark NLP.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
If you're into natural language processing,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
that's an extension that you want to check out.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
And you can take a look at all the extensions,

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.000
or at least some of them, under a new GitHub repo.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
It's at github.com slash rspark.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
A few more features on SparklyR 101.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
Qubole is, as I mentioned, added support for SparklyR on their clusters.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So if you happen to be a customer of Qubole,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
in order to use SparklyR from those clusters,

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
all you need to say is spark connect method equals Qubole.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.000
For those of you using Databricks, this is very similar to what we already have,

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.000
which is to connect to Databricks, you would say method equals Databricks.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
And that's pretty much it. It's quite simple and straightforward.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
There's also Spark 3.0 about to be released at some point this year.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
It's currently on preview, so that means that you don't want to use it for production.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.000
But basically, if you can't wait to try it out,

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:40.000
or you have workflows that you're planning to move to Spark 3.0,

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
this is a great way of trying it out.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
It adds new features like support for Java 11,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
GPU scheduling, and also binary files.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
So how do you use it from SparklyR?

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:58.000
Well, what you would do is basically you want to say spark install and then 3.0 preview.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:03.000
And that installs the 3.0 version, the preview version of 3.0 in your local machine.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
And then you just connect to Spark 3.0.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
We have a long tail of bugs, so it's definitely, you know, if you find issues,

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.000
let us know and we'll fix them.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
And in this particular example, what we're doing is we're downloading ImageNet.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
Well, actually a subset of ImageNet called TinyImageNet.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.000
And we're using the pins package to download it.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:26.000
And then we're loading that data set into Spark by using a new feature called binary file,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.000
which basically gives you a data frame with images in each row,

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
which you can use for deep learning or why not.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And this brings me to the last feature, which is pretty geeky, but I'm really excited about it.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.000
So one of the new kind of like trends that the Spark community has been noticing

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:47.000
is that if you look at the state of the art deep learning models,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:52.000
a lot of them, you know, several years ago, they all were trained with a single GPU.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
But if you look at newer models like AlphaGo or the open AIs,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:02.000
V versus 1, V1V or whatever it's called, 1V1 model,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.000
they all use more than one GPU to get trained.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And Spark trying to be this platform that allows you to run distributed workloads,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
it's adding support for something called barrier execution,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.000
which basically all it does, it gives control back to the cluster machines that you're using

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
for you to run either OpenMP or TensorFlow distributed or why not.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.000
So don't expect to use this user, don't expect to use this feature on your own.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
But, you know, like if you're an advanced user or maybe ourself,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
we'll create extensions on top of these that makes use of these functionality.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
But if you had to use it, you basically use Spark apply, you say barrier equals true.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:43.000
And then what you get is, you know, in this case, it's just a single machine.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:50.000
You would get basically the IP addresses and the ports that you can use to directly communicate to those machines.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
All right. So we're going to switch to MLflow.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And before we kind of like explain what MLflow is,

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
I want to kind of like present what's the problem that MLflow is trying to solve.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:06.000
And for that, I want to use a quote from Andrej Karpaty, which leads the self-driving effort at Tesla.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:12.000
And in one of his talks, he mentions that, you know, like the stack for software 2.0 doesn't exist.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
So what does that mean? So if you think of companies like, for instance, Netflix, right?

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:27.000
They have a bunch of movies and they need to do data science on those movies and to create a recommendation algorithm for you to, you know, to choose a movie to watch.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:32.000
Companies like Apple with Siri, they need to, you know, like do models around speech processing.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And companies like Tesla need to take capture images and then train deep learning models on top of them.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So you're probably familiar with these. You know, this is the standard kind of like data science approach where you get a data set and you create a model out of that.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:52.000
But then something that you can consider is also, well, if I already have this model, maybe I can make it part of my product.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:00.000
So things that Netflix does, for instance, is like they don't only create a recommendation model, but they deploy their recommendation model to their website.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Right. So you see the model being deployed there.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
If you're Apple and you're using Siri, you also have a model deployed on your phone.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And if you're Tesla and you're building self-driving cars, you also deploy that model to your cars.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So now you have models in production. So what do we do? What do you do with those?

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:24.000
Well, you usually want to collect data because there's a bunch of data that is meaningful to get either from your actual things that you're watching on Netflix or why not.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:30.000
And once you have the data, you kind of like want to tidy it because this data is usually pretty messy and you bring it back to the beginning.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:37.000
And the problem that this creates is that you usually don't only have one model. You have multiple models.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:43.000
You have multiple parameters that you're using to train your models. You have multiple versions of the data and you have multiple versions of the code.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:51.000
So it can be pretty easy to get into quite a mess while you're trying to do this faster and faster.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:56.000
So the MLflow project basically is an open source platform to manage the machine learning lifecycle.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:03.000
And you can use it from R as follows. It has three main features. MLflow tracking, MLflow projects and MLflow models.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:10.000
Tracking basically tracks your parameters and your metrics. Projects allows you to deploy to production your models.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:16.000
And the modeling component of this project allows you to perform inference on the models.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
In this particular example, all we're using is the tracking component of MLflow.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:28.000
And we're basically saying start a new MLflow experiment. Then we lock some parameters and we lock some metrics.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:34.000
So to put all this together, let's just take a quick look at how this all works together.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:43.000
And now it doesn't mean that you need to use Spark, MLflow and Delta Lake together.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:48.000
You can use them separately, right? But in this particular demo, we're going to basically use all of them at the same time.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:54.000
So first of all, we're defining some helper functions. And then we're connecting to Spark.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:01.000
And we're saying package equals Delta, which is the component that we mentioned is required when connecting to Spark.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:06.000
And then what we're going to do is we're going to download a data set that tracks wine quality.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:12.000
We're using the pins package for that. Then we're reading it as a CSV in Spark. And then we're writing it to Delta.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
Now, you usually wouldn't do this. You usually have a big data set already.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
But just for the purposes of this demo, this is what we're doing.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:25.000
So now the data is being written to Delta Lake. And then what we can do is we can use Spark to, first of all,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:28.000
log which is the version of our data that we're using.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:39.000
You can also log some of the parameters that we're going to be using in this case using GLM on Spark.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:46.000
So we're logging the parameters that our model is using. And we're also logging the actual metrics.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And you get that for free. It's automatic. And then you can use it.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:54.000
So suppose now that we didn't really like the performance of this model.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.000
And then it also happened to be the case that someone came along and replaced our data set or new data became available.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:08.000
So we have two things changing. One is the actual data set. And we also change our model. And we're going to rerun it.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:13.000
And again, this is mostly transparent. Once you start using MLflow, you're logging all these.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:19.000
But the great thing is that you can actually track these metrics by using the MLflow UI.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:24.000
And you can take a look at here. And we have two runs that we just performed.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:31.000
One of them has a lambda of 05. And it's using the version of Delta Lake 1 of the data frame.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And then we also have our previous run. You can see here that you have things like some metrics.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:44.000
And then you can drill down and look at this particular experiment and open up and look at it and say like, wow, this is looking great.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:50.000
And so you can add a node. Looking great. And you can also look at the metrics.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:15:00.000
You know, our particular run was pretty small. But if this was like a pretty long run, you could actually log the progress and see progress towards it.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.000
All right. So that covers kind of like everything else. And there's two more things that I want to share.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:11.000
So I know that there's a lot to learn. You know, in order to learn Spark and all these things in one 20 minute talk is impossible.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
So if you feel a little bit lost, don't worry. We have you covered.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:21.000
We wrote a book with O'Reilly, this book that you can just go and purchase. It's called Mastering Spark with R.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:28.000
It's on your favorite local store or online. And mostly it's a great resource for you to learn Spark.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:34.000
You can basically if you don't know anything about Spark whatsoever, just grab the book and read it start to finish.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:40.000
If you're an intermediate user, that's also fine. You probably will find tips and tricks that you didn't know about.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
And if you don't feel like buying it, that's also completely OK.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:49.000
You can go to the R in Spark.com and it's free to use there for you.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:56.000
And last but not least, I want to kind of like give a big shout out of thank you to the R community.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:00.000
The Sparkly R project, honestly, is just successful because of the R community.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:03.000
And there has been a lot of momentum going on.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:10.000
There's over 20 community extensions created for the Sparkly R project and there's over 50 contributors.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:17.000
But most most interestingly, there has one thing that has changed in the last six,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:25.000
the last three months kind of is that whilst our studio keeps being one of the main committers and supporters of the Sparkly R project,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:31.000
there is interest for other entities like Qubole and Databricks adding new features like Spark 3.0,

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:41.000
which was provided by Databricks. And, you know, like also, you know, a lot of good collaboration going on with the Ursa Labs project and Apache Arrow.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:51.000
So we definitely want to take Sparkly R to, you know, to be to even grow broader with our community and beyond our community.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:59.000
So the other announcement that we have for today is that Sparkly R is joining the Linux Foundation under the LFAI umbrella.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:08.000
This basically doesn't change anything as a user, but as a contributor, it changes a lot because basically that means that, you know, it should be much easier to contribute.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:16.000
It's also hosted within the Linux Foundation, which provides open governance and holds some of the project assets.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And, you know, other projects have trusted the Linux Foundation like Kubernetes, Delta Lake, Node.js, Horovod, and even Linux itself.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:30.000
So, yeah, if you want to learn more about it, go to our sassy URL, sparklyr.ai, and thank you.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:44.000
Thanks for that great talk.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
We've got a number of questions on Slido.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:53.000
So how will MLflow interact with Tidy Models, the Tidy Models ecosystem?

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
Yeah, I mean, that's a great question.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:59.000
I mean, the reality right now is that MLflow is pretty bare bones, as you noticed.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Like, you basically have to do everything on your own.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.000
You need to say MLflow log, so there's no interaction whatsoever.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:09.000
But it's definitely something on our radar that we would want to do so much better.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
So I'm sure we'll come up with something.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:15.000
But right now, you need to log manually the parameters.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Are the ML functions that run in a local Spark instance automatically multithreaded, or do we still need to use things like foreach, mcapply, et cetera?

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
No, it's actually multithreaded.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
So you can use Spark locally.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:32.000
And there might be some very few use cases for using Spark on a single instance on your local machine.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:36.000
But I honestly don't recommend it because Spark was designed to run on clusters.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:43.000
So, yes, you might get some performance improvements in some cases, but that's not the main use case for Spark anyways.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
So this is an interesting question.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Are there plans to make MLflow more enterprise-friendly with things like authentication, permissions, et cetera?

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.000
You should ask that question to Tarif if he's somewhere in here.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
But not to my knowledge.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:58.000
I know that Databricks has support for MLflow.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.000
So if you're a Databricks customer, it's quite easy to use MLflow on their platform.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:06.000
But if not, I think you'll have to hack something together, at least for now.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:07.000
Thank you.

